          "Comments",
          "Limitations"
        ],
        [
          "Regression",
          "MOOC",
          "E-Learning",
          "731 students in Canvas",
          "1 Computer Science Course",
          "LMS logs",
          "Not Applicable",
          "[L, D, A]",
          "Students labelled as dropouts were not considered for this course.\n\nEach row represents a student-module pairing. Multiple feature sets are created:\n\nL → activities associated with video lectures, \n\nA - Activities associated with assignments\n\nD - Discussion-Related Activities",
          "Poisson, \nHawkes (Single), Hawkes (Multi)",
          "L Features\n{RMSE: 0.56 - Hawkes (Multi)}\n\nA Features\n{RMSE: 2.34 - Hawkes (Multi)}\n\nD Features\n{RMSE: 1.37 - Hawkes (Multi)}",
          "2",
          "Group 1: Assignment to Video Leacture and Assignment to Discussion activities is much lower for this group than the other - Non-dealy group.\n\nGroup 2 - Delay Group → participation in activities is much more dictated by assignments. \n\n",
          "Dealines are big motivating factors for assignment-related activities. \n\nNon-delay learners have more frequent and less dense activities → suggesting a relationship between performance and being able to to tasks more frequently. \n\n",
          "Authors create a set of attempts at modelling procrastination. The authors use k-means clustering to identify 2 groups…. Non-delay vs delay.\n\nAnalysis of the results based on performance shows that there is a negative correlation between delay and performance. ",
          "Disregarding of Dropout students, as procratination is a decent predictor of dropout.\n\nOnly a single metric being evaluated.\n\nlimited number of predictors in a single context/dataset."
        ]
      ],
      "index": 6
    }
  ],
